## Hints & warnings
- CRITICAL: _is_retryable_exception defaults to RETRY (returns True) for any non-HTTPStatusError. So raising a *custom* exception for a 4xx would have made it retryable again -- the retry.py edit is what actually stops the retry. Letting the raw 400 HTTPStatusError propagate would already be non-retryable, but the user asked for explicit client handling and a catchable type.
- Client QueryTooExpensive (http_utils, no "Error" suffix) is a DISTINCT class from server QueryTooExpensiveError (errors.py); same split-naming convention as CallsCompleteModeRequired. retry.py imports the CLIENT one from http_utils (lazy, to avoid the http_utils->retry circular import).
- handle_response_error references the constant/class defined later in the same file; resolved at call time (matches existing CallsComplete pattern).

## Codebase discoveries
- Client retry policy lives entirely in weave/utils/retry.py (tenacity, retry_max_attempts()); retry_id generated per with_retry call = the retry_id seen on the Datadog spans.

